		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Post-Fordism</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Post-Fordism</b> is the name given to the dominant system of <a href="/wiki/Production,_costs,_and_pricing" title="Production, costs, and pricing" class="mw-redirect">economic production</a>, <a href="/wiki/Consumption" title="Consumption">consumption</a> and associated socio-economic phenomena, in most <a href="/wiki/Industrialized" title="Industrialized" class="mw-redirect">industrialized</a> countries since the late 20th century. It is contrasted with <a href="/wiki/Fordism" title="Fordism">Fordism</a>, the system formulated in <a href="/wiki/Henry_Ford" title="Henry Ford">Henry Ford</a>'s automotive factories, in which workers work on a <a href="/wiki/Production_line" title="Production line">production line</a>, performing specialized tasks repetitively. Definitions of the nature and scope of Post-Fordism vary considerably and are a matter of debate among scholars.</p>
<p>Post-Fordism is characterized by the following attributes<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Small-batch production.</li>
<li>Economies of scope.</li>
<li>Specialized products and jobs.</li>
<li>New information technologies.</li>
<li>Emphasis on types of consumers in contrast to previous emphasis on social class.</li>
<li>The rise of the service and the <a href="/wiki/White-collar" title="White-collar" class="mw-redirect">white-collar</a> worker.</li>
<li>The feminization of the work force.</li>
</ul>
